            <span class="cta-meta">24-hour delivery · No card</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-stacc">theStacc vs AIOSEO — honest comparison</h2>
        <p>We wrote this review. We compete. Read the comparison first so you can weigh everything that follows.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>AIOSEO</th><th>theStacc</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>$49/yr (~$4/mo)</td><td>$99/mo</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Works outside WordPress</td><td class="cell-no">WordPress only</td><td class="cell-yes">WordPress + Webflow + Ghost</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Setup wizard</td><td class="cell-yes">Best-in-class</td><td>Not needed — managed</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Schema markup (40+ types)</td><td class="cell-yes">Pro tier</td><td class="cell-yes">Automatic</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Articles written for you</td><td class="cell-no">None — config tool</td><td class="cell-yes">30 / month</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Auto-publishes content</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Google Business Profile posts</td><td class="cell-no">Not included</td><td class="cell-yes">30 GBP posts / month</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Rank tracking</td><td class="cell-no">Not included</td><td class="cell-yes">Daily</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Done-for-you</td><td class="cell-no">DIY config + content</td><td class="cell-yes">Fully managed</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Real monthly cost (plugin + writers + ops)</strong></td><td>$2,503–$7,754</td><td><strong>$99 flat</strong></td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where AIOSEO wins:</strong> if WordPress is your CMS and you have writers, AIOSEO Pro is the easiest configuration plugin on the market. <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> if your job is growing organic traffic without building a content team. Pick by the job.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is AIOSEO?</h2>
        <p>AIOSEO (All in One SEO Pack) is a WordPress plugin first released in 2007. After ownership changes, it was acquired by <strong>Awesome Motive</strong> (the company behind WPForms, OptinMonster, and MonsterInsights) in 2020. It now powers SEO configuration on <strong>3+ million active WordPress sites</strong>, making it the second-largest plugin in the category after Yoast.</p>

        <p>What AIOSEO actually does:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>On-page SEO</strong> — title tags, meta descriptions, focus keyword analysis, content scoring</li>
          <li><strong>Schema markup</strong> — 40+ structured-data types (Article, Product, FAQ, Recipe, LocalBusiness, etc.)</li>
          <li><strong>XML sitemaps</strong> — auto-generated with smart pagination for large sites</li>
          <li><strong>Redirects manager</strong> — 301/302/307 with full match history (Pro tier)</li>
          <li><strong>Local SEO</strong> — LocalBusiness schema, GBP integration, multi-location (Pro / Elite)</li>
          <li><strong>WooCommerce SEO</strong> — product schema, category-page optimization (Pro)</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What AIOSEO is <em>not</em>: a writer, a research tool, a rank tracker, or a publishing platform. It is a configuration layer over your WordPress install — nothing more.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>Acquired by Awesome Motive (WPForms, OptinMonster, MonsterInsights) in 2020. The acquisition modernized the codebase — old AIOSEO from the 2010s was a mess. Today the plugin ships clean code, regular updates, and tier-one support. The trade-off: pricing climbed sharply post-acquisition. The setup wizard is the best in the category and remains the single biggest reason new WordPress users pick AIOSEO over RankMath.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">AIOSEO features — the 2026 walkthrough</h2>

        <h3>1. Setup wizard — genuinely best-in-class</h3>
        <p>The setup wizard is the headline feature. It walks first-time users through 6 steps: site type, business info, social profiles, sitemap setup, additional features, and a smart-import from Yoast or RankMath if you are migrating. Most users complete it in under 5 minutes and ship a fully configured SEO install. RankMath's setup is similar but more cluttered; Yoast's feels dated. This is where AIOSEO actually earns its premium.</p>

        <h3>2. Schema markup (40+ types)</h3>
        <p>Schema support is broad: Article, BlogPosting, NewsArticle, Product, Recipe, Course, Event, FAQ, HowTo, JobPosting, LocalBusiness (with 250+ subtypes), Movie, Restaurant, Service, Software, VideoObject. The Schema Generator is wizard-driven — point-and-click rather than JSON editing. Beats Yoast's schema (limited) but comparable to RankMath Pro.</p>

        <h3>3. Sitemaps + RSS feeds</h3>
        <p>Auto-generated XML sitemap with HTML sitemap option, news sitemap (Pro tier), video sitemap (Pro tier), and RSS optimization. Smart pagination handles sites with 50k+ URLs without timing out — important if you run an ecommerce or directory site.</p>

        <h3>4. Redirects manager (Pro)</h3>
        <p>Full 301/302/307 redirect manager with regex support, 404 monitoring, and bulk CSV import. Critical for site migrations. The catch: RankMath includes redirects in its <em>free</em> tier. AIOSEO gates this behind Pro at $199/yr.</p>

        <h3>5. Local SEO (Pro)</h3>
        <p>LocalBusiness schema with hours, departments, services, and Google Business Profile integration. Multi-location support requires Elite. Solid but not a replacement for a dedicated local SEO platform (Whitespark, BrightLocal, theStacc Local SEO module).</p>

        <h3>6. Link Assistant (Elite)</h3>
        <p>Internal linking suggestions based on content analysis. Genuinely useful for sites with 100+ articles. Elite-tier only at $299/yr.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">AIOSEO pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Plan</th><th>Annual</th><th>Per mo</th><th>Sites</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Basic</strong></td><td>$49.50/yr</td><td>~$4</td><td>1</td><td>Single blog, on-page only</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Plus</strong></td><td>$99.50/yr</td><td>~$8</td><td>3</td><td>News + author / SEO Analysis</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Pro</strong></td><td>$199.50/yr</td><td>~$17</td><td>10</td><td>Schema + Local + Redirects (sweet spot)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Elite</strong></td><td>$299.50/yr</td><td>~$25</td><td>100</td><td>Agencies + Link Assistant + multi-location</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>Year-one pricing only — renewal jumps typically run 50–100% in year two unless you cancel and re-buy through a coupon. There is a free version with reduced schema, no redirects, no local, and 1 focus keyword. Most paid users land on Pro.</p>

        <h3>The real monthly cost most reviews skip</h3>
        <p>AIOSEO configures your SEO. It does not write a word. To actually rank with AIOSEO installed, here is the real monthly math:</p>

        <div class="cost-calc">
          <div class="cc-head">
            <div>
