              <span>You save</span>
              <span><strong>$3,998 /mo</strong> · or <strong>$47,976 / year</strong></span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cc-foot">
            <p>Want the same output for a fraction of the cost? Let's see if your site qualifies.</p>
            <a href="/demo/">Get my free audit →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">⚠️ The execution math</div>
          <p>Every WordPress site owner we interviewed underestimated the real SEO cost by <strong>20×</strong>. They saw a $199/yr plugin and budgeted $17/mo. They actually spend $2,500–$5,000/mo to turn that configuration into published, ranking pages. AIOSEO is honest about what it does — the gap is in how owners calculate their <em>real</em> SEO budget.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta dark">
          <div class="cta-copy">
            <h4>Wondering if buying AIOSEO makes more sense than hiring an SEO team?</h4>
            <p>We'll audit your site and show you exactly what would generate the highest ROI for <strong>your</strong> business — DIY plugin, agency, or done-for-you platform.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cta-action">
            <a href="/demo/" class="cta-btn-inline">Book my strategy call <span>→</span></a>
            <span class="cta-meta">30-min · No pitch</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="pros-cons">Pros and cons after 30 days</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>✓ What AIOSEO gets right</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Cleanest setup wizard in the category — under 5 minutes</li>
              <li>40+ schema types with point-and-click Schema Generator</li>
              <li>Smart import from Yoast and RankMath (zero data loss)</li>
              <li>Modern codebase post-Awesome Motive acquisition</li>
              <li>Tier-one support — fast responses, real humans</li>
              <li>WooCommerce SEO actually works on product + category pages</li>
              <li>Local SEO module covers multi-location on Elite</li>
              <li>Link Assistant (Elite) saves hours on internal linking</li>
              <li>Smart sitemap pagination handles 50k+ URLs without timeouts</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>✗ Where AIOSEO hurts</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Pricier than RankMath for similar feature set</li>
              <li>Free version is heavily restricted (1 focus keyword, no redirects)</li>
              <li>Renewal pricing jumps 50–100% in year two</li>
              <li>WordPress-only — no Webflow, Ghost, or Shopify support</li>
              <li>No content writing or AI-content tools (small title generator only)</li>
              <li>No rank tracking — you still need Ahrefs / Semrush / a tracker</li>
              <li>Schema generator can over-bloat pages if mis-configured</li>
              <li>Aggressive upsell prompts inside the WP admin</li>
              <li>License-key activation friction across multiple sites</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="inline-cta">
          <div class="cta-copy">
            <h4>Don't want another WordPress plugin to manage?</h4>
            <p>theStacc handles SEO config, content, GBP, and ranks — without you ever opening a dashboard. <strong>Try it for $1</strong>, cancel anytime.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="cta-action">
            <a href="/checkout/" class="cta-btn-inline">Start $1 trial <span>→</span></a>
            <span class="cta-meta">No annual contract</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="performance">Performance — does AIOSEO actually work?</h2>
        <p>AIOSEO does not <em>create</em> rankings. It configures WordPress so Google can read your site cleanly. On that narrow job, it performs well — sites we audited showed clean schema validation, fast sitemap regeneration, and zero crawl errors after install.</p>

        <div class="stat-grid">
          <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">3M+</div><div class="stat-lbl">Active WordPress installs</div></div>
          <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">40+</div><div class="stat-lbl">Schema markup types</div></div>
          <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">&lt;5 min</div><div class="stat-lbl">Setup wizard completion</div></div>
          <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">50k+</div><div class="stat-lbl">URLs in sitemap, no timeout</div></div>
        </div>

        <h3>AIOSEO vs RankMath vs Yoast — the WordPress plugin war</h3>

        <div class="chart-card">
          <div class="chart-head">
            <div>
              <div class="chart-title">WordPress active installs (millions · 2026)</div>
              <div class="chart-sub">wordpress.org plugin directory</div>
            </div>
            <div class="chart-legend">
              <span class="lg-1">AIOSEO</span>
              <span class="lg-2">Competitor</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="bar-rows">
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">Yoast SEO</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill alt" style="width: 100%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">13M+</span></div>
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">RankMath</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill alt" style="width: 25%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">3.2M</span></div>
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">AIOSEO</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill" style="width: 23%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">3.0M</span></div>
            <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">SEOPress</span><div class="bar-track"><div class="bar-fill alt" style="width: 2%"></div></div><span class="bar-value">~300k</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Install share lies.</strong> Yoast's free version has been the default for a decade — but most pros migrated to RankMath (free tier is more generous) or AIOSEO (cleaner UX). New WordPress installs in 2026 skew toward RankMath for cost-sensitive users and AIOSEO for agencies that need polish and support.</p>

        <blockquote class="pull">
          "AIOSEO is the plugin I install on every client site that pays for premium support. RankMath is the plugin I install on every client site that does not. The features are 85% identical."
          <cite>— Agency owner, 40+ WordPress sites managed</cite>
        </blockquote>

        <h2 id="who-its-for">Who AIOSEO is best for — and who should skip</h2>

        <h3>Strong fit</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>WordPress agencies managing client sites that need reliable support</li>
          <li>WooCommerce stores needing product / category schema</li>
          <li>News and publisher sites needing news + video sitemaps</li>
          <li>Local businesses on WordPress needing LocalBusiness schema</li>
